From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: focused dump on affected CPU +
 per-CPU snapshot recording on all other cores at 3s

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop() when active_load_balance_cpu_stop() triggers a nested
stop_one_cpu_nowait() via:

  finish_task_switch()
    -> run_balance_callbacks()
      -> sched_balance_rq() OR balance_push()
        -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()   <-- re-entrancy while already executing
                                        inside stop_two_cpus / multi_cpu_stop

==========================================================================
Design (v3 -- focused dump + per-CPU snapshot)
==========================================================================

Previous approach called trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() from the dump owner,
which sends IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE to all cores and waits for each to respond.
This introduced the risk of per-CPU IPI timeout (10s/CPU on arm64 if any
core has IRQs disabled) and produced interleaved output.

This version splits responsibilities cleanly:

  EVERY CPU that detects the 3s timeout (including the owner):
    Step 1 -- Write a lightweight per-CPU snapshot into its OWN percpu
              slot. Writing to own percpu slot is always safe -- no locks,
              no contention, no races regardless of how many CPUs detect
              simultaneously.
    Step 2 -- atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner, -1, cpu):
              ONE CPU wins and becomes the dump owner.
              ALL others enter: while(1) cpu_relax() + touch_nmi_watchdog()

  DUMP OWNER (the affected/detecting CPU):
    - Full diagnostic dump of ITSELF (Sec1-5): outer fn, msdata, CPU
      masks, own stopper state, own dump_stack().
    - Then reads all other CPUs' percpu snapshots (Sec6) and prints them
      sequentially -- clean, single-threaded, zero interleaving.
    - panic() immediately.

  NON-OWNER CPUs:
    - Already wrote their snapshot in Step 1 before entering the spin.
    - Spin in while(1) cpu_relax() + touch_nmi_watchdog().
    - Owner's panic() brings them down.

==========================================================================
Per-CPU snapshot struct (stopper_cpu_snapshot)
==========================================================================

Each CPU fills in its own percpu slot when it detects the timeout:

  struct stopper_cpu_snapshot {
      unsigned int   cpu;         /* which CPU this snapshot is from    */
      int            curstate;    /* multi_stop_state at timeout moment  */
      bool           is_active;   /* was this the active (fn-running) CPU*/
      void          *fn;          /* cpu_stopper->fn at snapshot time    */
      unsigned long  caller;      /* cpu_stopper->caller at snapshot time*/
      unsigned long  elapsed_j;   /* jiffies elapsed since spin entry    */
      bool           valid;       /* set last -- signals owner to print  */
  };

  valid is written LAST after all other fields are populated (store
  ordering enforced by smp_wmb() between payload writes and valid=true).
  Owner reads valid with READ_ONCE() to decide whether to print a slot.
  No lock needed: each CPU writes only its own slot, owner only reads.

==========================================================================
Why this is better than trigger_all_cpu_backtrace()
==========================================================================

trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() (IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE):
  - Sends IPI to each CPU and waits up to 10s for a response.
  - On arm64, if ANY target CPU has IRQs disabled: 10s timeout per CPU.
  - In PREPARE state: IRQs are ON, so the IPI itself is fast.
  - But in other contexts (e.g. a mix of PREPARE and DISABLE_IRQ):
    could add up to 10s * N_cpus of blocking before panic().
  - Output interleaves with owner dump output.
  - Removed in this patch.

Per-CPU snapshot approach:
  - Zero IPI, zero cross-CPU communication.
  - Each CPU writes only to its own percpu slot at the moment it detects
    the timeout. This is already happening (each CPU independently spins
    at position C) -- we just add a 5-field struct write before the spin.
  - Owner reads all slots sequentially after its own dump -- fully
    serialized, clean output, bounded time (<1ms total).
  - Captures curstate, is_active, fn, caller at the EXACT moment of
    timeout detection on each CPU -- more precise than IPI backtrace.

==========================================================================
TIMELINE
==========================================================================

  T=0s    deadlock begins (active CPU stuck at ack_state(PREPARE))

  T=3s    time_after() fires on one or more CPUs at position C
          Each detecting CPU:
            (a) fills in per_cpu(stopper_snapshot, cpu)  [lockless, own slot]
            (b) atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner, -1, cpu)

          ONE CPU wins (owner):
            Sec1: outer stopper fn + caller              (<50ms)
            Sec2: multi_stop_data state                  (<50ms)
            Sec3: CPU masks                              (<50ms)
            Sec4: own CPU stopper state (detailed)       (<100ms)
            Sec5: own dump_stack()                       (~100ms)
            Sec6: read + print all percpu snapshots      (<10ms)
                  (sequential, no IPI, no cross-CPU wait)
            panic() immediately

          ALL others (non-owners):
            Spin: while(1) { cpu_relax(); touch_nmi_watchdog(); }
            Owner's panic() brings them down.

  T~3.5s  panic() called -- ramdump captured
  T=11s   Qualcomm bark_time (worst case) -- ~7.5s safety margin

==========================================================================
rcu_momentary_eqs() interaction (position B)
==========================================================================

rcu_momentary_eqs() is called at position B:
  else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
      touch_nmi_watchdog();
      rcu_momentary_eqs();
  }

The caller contract (from kernel/rcu/tree_plugin.h):
  "The caller must have disabled interrupts and must not be idle."

In the PREPARE-state deadlock: curstate == PREPARE, so the condition
(curstate > PREPARE) is FALSE. Position B is NEVER entered. IRQs remain
ON. rcu_momentary_eqs() never runs. Its local_irq_save() path inside
rcu_preempt_deferred_qs() is therefore not a concern.

In normal (non-deadlock) paths: position B is reached in DISABLE_IRQ or
RUN states where IRQs are already disabled. rcu_momentary_eqs() safely
calls local_irq_save() on an already-disabled state. Jiffies stay frozen.
time_after() stays false. No false positive.

This confirms the IRQ-off false-positive guard works correctly for all
non-deadlock states, independent of rcu_momentary_eqs() behavior.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'. 'int cpu' is a pre-existing
mismatch vs cpumask_test_cpu(unsigned int,...) and per_cpu_ptr(...,
unsigned int). Clang 19 warns at every call site.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Position C unconditional detection (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

  do {
    if (curstate < msdata->state) { ... }
    if (is_active)       ack_state(msdata);         /* A */
    else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
        touch_nmi_watchdog(); rcu_momentary_eqs();  /* B: not in PREPARE */
    }
    /* C: ALL CPUs, ALL states, every iteration */
    if (!timed_out && time_after(...)) { ... }
  } while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================

- Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
- No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
- Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible
- atomic_cmpxchg(): <linux/atomic.h> via kernel.h -- already included
- DEFINE_PER_CPU(): <linux/percpu.h> -- already included in stop_machine.c
- smp_wmb() / READ_ONCE(): unconditionally available
- show_state(): <linux/sched/debug.h> -- always present in GKI
- jiffies / HZ / time_after(): unconditionally available
- No trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() -- removed (IPI hazard, not needed)

